A film by @type7

Son of legendary Australian shaper and surfer Neal Purchase, Neal Purchase Jnr was more or less born into the profession and culture. Growing up competing, Neal found his way as a free surfer, later following his father’s footsteps as a shaper. Now, Neal is renowned internationally for his surfing ability as well as his craftsmanship.

His iconic Duo, Quartet and Single fin shapes are a modern day homage to the past, something he credits to his father’s influence. An ever evolving refinement of classic designs, Neal’s boards are just as much a work of art as they are high performance surf craft. 

Yet despite his status in the surf world, 'Purcho' is one of the most kind, humble people you will meet. In fact, he scored the soundtrack for this very film 🏄‍♂️

Directed by @caplice
Starring @nealpurchasejnr
Production Company @mojaveproductions

node.text:
Built in the forest of Costa Rica, this treehouse is a bit of a departure from the work we’re used to seeing from Olson Kundig (@olsonkundig). The Seattle based studio tends to work in the colder regions of rural North America, having cultivated a style that suits it very well. Little of that is present in this more tropical commission, though that hasn’t stopped them from producing magic.

The clients are surfers, so the top floor of the house is designed as a lookout spot perched above the trees where there’s a clear view of the beach. From there they can gauge whether or not it’s worth a day on the water. When it isn’t, the house is hardly a rough second choice. Warm, open and wholly organic throughout, it’s a far cry from the hard, industrial designs we’re used to from OK.

Teak makes up the majority of the woodwork. The self oiling hardwood is perfect for exterior construction and it grows locally, so very little of the building’s mass has had to travel very far. Even the pillars inside are tree trunks, lightly refinished but in keeping with their natural form. Sure it’s a departure from their regular schedule, but it’s a knock out piece none the less.

Photos by Nic Lehoux
Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7

The best encounters in far away lands always happen by chance. We had just finished a long day exploring Tbilisi Sea in Georgia, a large natural lake about 20 minutes from downtown Tbilisi with our friends @dimitridugladze11 and @alexjaparidze when they asked if we would be down to meet “George”.

“George” as it turns out is passionate about two things: rescuing and restoring Soviet era industrial architecture, and collecting Porsches. We arrived at his warehouse, which if you are familiar with Soviet era architecture is immediately recognizable. The USSR had several templates for how structures such as this one were built, and as a result you can find identical buildings dotted all across former Soviet Republics and Russia itself. They are, for lack of a better word: bombproof. 

Sturdy, safe, and built to last they make the perfect foundations for projects whose aim is to create new life where there once was industrial malaise. Enter George, who is in the process of redeveloping this site to, amongst other things, host his Porsche collection in a safe environment.

“I wanted to have a perfect example of each major era of Porsche’s evolution, this is about as far as I have gotten.” He explains to us; “the best way to do that for Georgian Nationals has been to import from Japan. Until recently there was not a huge market in Georgia for Porsches, so we had to look elsewhere. The Japanese maintain their cars meticulously, so I try to source everything I drive from that market. It’s something like a labor of love.”

What’s missing also from this photo is George’s 993 Carrera, which we had the pleasure of driving all weekend: “when you have 9 Porsches it’s important that you let your friends enjoy them, it helps keep them exercised.”

Photos and words by @tedgushue for @type7

node.text:
Built on a remote peninsula of south western Tasmania, this house of glass was built by Room11 (@room11__). Two parallel lines define the design, nothing more. The best architecture often plays tribute to its surroundings, this does so by disappearing altogether. Houses like these are almost a genre of their own at this point. First posited in the Farnsworth House by Mies van der Rohe, the objective is to minimise the tools of living down to their barest essentials. Call it superleggera living if you like.

To be clear, this is a thought exercise, it will not be permanently inhabited and neither should it be. This is a pavilion, located a short distance from a more permanent living space. One might spend at a few days here at a time, but little more. As an inhabitant, the idea of living up to the promise of a space like this is in the long run, unsustainable, maybe even unpleasant. But it’s a touch of the divine, the horizon of modernist aspirations.

Photos by @adam.gibson.photo
Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7

node.text:
If and when you are able to taste a drop of the divine juice from a world renowned wine producer like Petrus you will consider yourself remarkably lucky. Not just because each bottle sells for north of €2000 on the open market, and not just because it genuinely is one of the highest quality winemakers in the Bordeaux region.

You will consider yourself lucky because this producer, which enjoys a remarkable reputation and brand awareness worldwide, produces so few bottles on such little land that the fact it exists at all is almost completely at odds with the reality of the terroir from which it is grown and bottled.

I recently had the pleasure of tasting the 2020 En Premieur while visiting Pomerol, which included a tour of the property and its Chateau. The land they grow on comprise a total of 11.4 hectares, generating around 30,000 bottles annually at an average retail price of €2000/bottle. To put this in perspective, Chateau Lynch Bages comprises 90 hectares, generating around 30,000 bottles at a retail price of €120/Bottle. It makes Petrus one of the most profitable wineries per hectare in the world.

The secret allegedly is in the earth, with a preposterously high clay content the vines are treated to a consistent source of water through the dense and moist earth allowing them to grow consistently perfect merlot grapes even in the hottest of seasons. This clay content does not exist anywhere else at this level in the region; a truly coveted gem of land for professional grape farmers.

You might expect the Chateau to be a grandiose affair and yet it’s the exact opposite: restrained, elegant, clean and simple, almost zen like. There are less than 25 employees; it is calm, controlled and collected.  There is no air of self importance about the staff considering they are making one of the world’s most expensive and sought after wines. The team are calm, kind and relaxed. One might even go so far as to say chilled. But maybe that’s the only way it could be when you are making grape juice of the highest possible caliber.

Photos and words by @tedgushue for @type7

node.text:
Leonberg, near Stuttgart, is most famous for its picturesque market square, the centuries-old annual horse market, its past role as seat of one of Baden-Württemberg’s first parliaments, and the Pomeranzen Garden, aka Germany’s only remaining terraced garden dating back to the late Renaissance. Another thing this small city located on the east side of Glems river is renowned for is its fondness in tuning already fast cars.

Here in 1981 Uwe Gemballa opened a shop specialized in selling aftermarket parts mainly for Porsche. Despite the noir stories hidden behind the disappearance of its founder in 2010, Gemballa made – and still makes, under new name Gemballa GmbH – breathtaking Porsche-based supercars.

A 600 hp Gemballa model held the lap record for road cars at the Nürburgring in the late 1990s once, and again in 2001 when Wolfgang Kaufmann lowered it to 7:32,52 min. It was since beaten by a stock Carrera GT by less than a second.

For the Biturbo GTR those crazy Leonberg guys took a 996 GT3 and, basically, did a tasteful twin turbo upgrade. So, a couple of KKK K24.2 working between 0,8 and 0,9 bars pair with an intercooler duo and few other interesting features such as separate engine water/oil cooler, a modified gearbox with its own oil radiator and an inox-forged Gemballa-made sport exhaust.

To cope with the increased power figures of 630 hp at 7.000 rpm and 650 Nm of torque at 5.500 rpm, there is a 19” wheels set hiding a Brembo braking system with 8 piston calipers at the front and 4 calipers at the back. Top speed is 340+ km/h, acceleration on 0-100 km/h is under 4 seconds. A distinctive Gemballa-designed rear spoiler – icing on the cake – prevent the car from taking off.

When Germans come to tuning, there are no compromises.

Thanks to our friends @car_vintage for sharing this story with us.

Photos by @defuntis
Words by @d1fretta

node.text:
Author, jazz musician, classical composer, magazine editor, poet and film director. Gordon Parks never even attained a high school diploma, and yet he lived ten lifetimes in one. However, it was his photography most of all that made him one of the all time great American artists.

What you get with Gordon Parks is variety. Assembled together, you’d think his work was a compilation of a dozen separate master photographers. Monochrome alongside colour, civil rights activism as well as celebrity culture, photojournalism and fashion photography. Sometimes he mixed genres, other times his photos were much more pure. 

Simply put, it was impossible to box Gordon Parks in, despite the world trying to; “If for instance I had been born a rich white boy, gone to Harvard or Yale,” he said in a 2000 interview, “life would have been different. I’d have been expected to be a physician, or a lawyer, or a scientist, or something I would have had to stick to. But I didn’t finish high school and I was frightened to death of failure. There wasn’t any genius attached to my life, it was just a matter of being able to eat breakfast in the morning after my mother died.”

His talent as a polymath came together most beautifully in 1969 when he became the first African American to be commissioned by a Hollywood studio to direct a feature film with “The Learning Tree”. In true Gordon Parks style, he also wrote the soundtrack and adapted the screenplay from the 1963 novel of the same name. You guessed it, he wrote that too.

If the pigeon holes of life were set on rejecting Parks then so be it, he’d soar higher without their shackles anyway. He’s a man who can’t be summed up in 2000 short characters, people have tried and failed to do that in much longer form. In truth, the story of his life was only ever told properly once, and it took him 93 years to tell it. 

Photos via Gordon Parks Archive
Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7

node.text:
Oscar Niemeyer’s own home is surprisingly modest for a titan of architecture credited with being one of the dozen or so master designers who thrust modernism into the mainstream. Both at home and abroad, his works were characterised by their curvaceousness and scale, including several of Brazil’s most important governmental structures, which completely buck the trend of greek and romanesque revivalism so often adopted by similar buildings around the world.

His home in the forest that you see above was built in 1951 near Rio de Janeiro, it’s similar in many ways to pavilions by Mies van der Rohe or Corbusier, but it’s perhaps more in tune with its surroundings. It doesn’t feel like a spaceship or a bunker as so often these things can; nature is abhorred by straight lines and so was Niemeyer. Architecture for him wasn’t about holding the line between civilisation and the chaos of the great outdoors, in fact so much of the house seems to invite the outside in.

Oscar Niemeyer is often seen as part of a collective these days but when examined more closely, you begin to see the unique contribution he made to the movement and why Brazil still champions him as one of the country’s all time greats. His grander projects might hold the limelight, but the story is incomplete without a small house in the trees, quietly minding its own business at the tranquil speed of nature.

Photos by Nelson Kon
Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7
